{"session_id":"svc-1778559259719736683","seq":0,"type":"session.start","ts":"2026-05-12T04:14:21.775332152Z","data":{"provider":"","model":"gpt-5.4-mini","sticky":{"key_present":true,"bonus":0},"utilization":{"observed_at":"0001-01-01T00:00:00Z"},"requested_harness":"codex","resolved_harness":"codex","harness_source":"request_harness","requested_model":"gpt-5.4-mini","resolved_model":"gpt-5.4-mini","work_dir":"/tmp/ddx-exec-wt/.execute-bead-wt-ddx-9d7ef3a6-20260512T041407-84b2cff5","max_iterations":0,"prompt":"\u003cexecute-bead\u003e\n  \u003cinstructions\u003e\nYou are executing one bead inside an isolated DDx execution worktree. The bead\u0026#39;s \u0026lt;description\u0026gt; and \u0026lt;acceptance\u0026gt; are the completion contract — every AC must be provably satisfied by a specific code, test, or file you can point to after your commit.\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;## Step 0: size check\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;Too big if any holds:\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;- More than ~6 ACs spanning unrelated subsystems.\u0026#xA;- AC mixes design, implementation, integration tests, and docs as separate deliverables.\u0026#xA;- Description names multiple feature-sized sub-pieces.\u0026#xA;- More than ~500 lines across ~5+ files in unrelated packages.\u0026#xA;- If the bead description exceeds 8000 bytes, treat Step 0 as a split-first pass.\u0026#xA;- Auto-decomposition is capped at depth 2: root beads may split once, decomposed children once more; third-level splits must be rejected with an explanation.\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;If too big, decompose — do not attempt the work:\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;1. `ddx bead create` for each child slice (copy parent\u0026#39;s labels and spec-id).\u0026#xA;2. `ddx bead dep add \u0026lt;child-id\u0026gt; \u0026lt;parent-id\u0026gt;` to record edges.\u0026#xA;3. `ddx bead update \u0026lt;parent-id\u0026gt; --notes \u0026#39;decomposed into \u0026lt;child-ids\u0026gt;\u0026#39;`.\u0026#xA;4. Write `.ddx/executions/20260512T041407-84b2cff5/no_changes_rationale.txt` listing child IDs, then stop.\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;A clean decomposition is a success. Do not mix implementation with decomposition.\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;## How to work\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;- Read first. If the bead names files, specs, or prior beads, read them before editing — do not guess.\u0026#xA;- Cross-reference each AC against concrete evidence (test name, file path, function) before committing. If you cannot point at it, it is not done.\u0026#xA;- Run the project\u0026#39;s test and lint commands before committing. **Do not commit red code** — fix failures first.\u0026#xA;- Stage with `git add \u0026lt;specific-paths\u0026gt;`; never `git add -A` (the worktree may have unrelated WIP).\u0026#xA;- Commit exactly once when green; conventional-commit subject ending with `[\u0026lt;bead-id\u0026gt;]`. Stop after the commit.\u0026#xA;- Do not modify files outside the bead\u0026#39;s scope.\u0026#xA;- If you cannot finish, write `.ddx/executions/20260512T041407-84b2cff5/no_changes_rationale.txt` (what is done, what blocks, what a follow-up needs) before exiting. No commit and no rationale ⇒ DDx records `no_evidence_produced`. A well-justified no_changes beats a bad commit.\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;## no_changes contract\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;`.ddx/executions/20260512T041407-84b2cff5/no_changes_rationale.txt` must contain one:\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;- `verification_command: \u0026lt;cmd\u0026gt;` — repo cwd; exit 0 closes, nonzero rejects.\u0026#xA;- `status: open` + `reason: \u0026lt;retryable\u0026gt;` — open, smart retry.\u0026#xA;- `status: proposed` + `reason: \u0026lt;operator needed\u0026gt;` — operator lane.\u0026#xA;- `status: blocked` + `reason: \u0026lt;external blocker\u0026gt;` — blocked lane.\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;No pseudo-statuses. Bare rationales and `status: needs_investigation` reject.\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;To request orchestrator decomposition, add `orchestrator_action: decompose` alongside `status: open`.\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;## Reports\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;Freestanding artifacts (investigation reports, findings docs) go under `.ddx/executions/20260512T041407-84b2cff5/` (the per-attempt evidence directory under `.ddx/executions/`). **Never write reports to `/tmp` or any path outside the repository** — out-of-repo paths are invisible to the post-merge reviewer and cause BLOCK on missing evidence. If the bead names a specific in-repo path, use it; else default to `.ddx/executions/20260512T041407-84b2cff5/\u0026lt;short-name\u0026gt;.md`. Stage and commit the report alongside code.\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;## Mode and overrides\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;DDX_MODE=bead_execution: edit code/docs for bead AC. Only broad queue-steward default is overridden; tracker, merge-policy, verification, safety stay active. Bead description/AC override CLAUDE.md, AGENTS.md, and project defaults.\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;## Review gate\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;- The review is a gate, not an escape hatch — meet every AC in this pass.\u0026#xA;- Address every BLOCKING `\u0026lt;review-findings\u0026gt;` item; do not declare `no_changes` with blocking findings open.\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;## Constraints\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;- Work only inside this execution worktree.\u0026#xA;- Keep `.ddx/executions/` intact — DDx uses it as execution evidence.\u0026#xA;- **Never run `ddx init`** — the workspace is initialized; running it corrupts the bead queue.\u0026#xA;- Do not modify files outside the bead\u0026#39;s named scope.\u0026#xA;- Do not rewrite CLAUDE.md, AGENTS.md, or other project-instructions files unless the bead asks.\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;## When the work is done\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;After the commit succeeds and every AC is verified, stop. Return control to the orchestrator — do not keep exploring or testing.\n  \u003c/instructions\u003e\n  \u003cbead id=\"ddx-9d7ef3a6\"\u003e\n    \u003ctitle\u003edocprose: add corpus harness for normalized findings\u003c/title\u003e\n    \u003cdescription\u003e\nPROBLEM\u0026#xA;DDx needs a labeled evaluation corpus before prose rules can be trusted. Without positive and negative fixtures, rule changes can claim success while producing structural false positives or missing AI-slop constructions.\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;ROOT CAUSE\u0026#xA;docs/helix/02-design/plan-2026-05-06-prose-quality-integration.md:132-191 defines corpus groups, metrics, and gates, but no corpus harness or golden normalized findings exist.\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;SMART JUSTIFICATION: Corpus design is high-judgment work. It decides which prose findings count as useful, which technical density must stay quiet, and how DDx avoids optimizing for detector-like noise instead of actionable documentation quality.\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;PROPOSED FIX\u0026#xA;- Add `cli/internal/docprose/testdata/corpus/` with positive, negative, and real DDx excerpt groups.\u0026#xA;- Add a corpus loader and expected normalized-finding JSON schema.\u0026#xA;- Add tests that compare normalized DDx findings, not raw Vale output.\u0026#xA;- Include negative samples for paths, commands, tables, frontmatter, IDs, API names, and acceptance criteria.\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;NON-SCOPE\u0026#xA;- Do not tune every Vale rule in this bead.\u0026#xA;- Do not switch the public command to Vale.\u0026#xA;- Do not run a full-doc cleanup.\u0026#xA;\u0026#xA;DEPS\u0026#xA;Depends on the style-pack skeleton so the corpus harness can target packaged DDx rules.\n    \u003c/description\u003e\n    \u003cacceptance\u003e\n1. `TestDocProseCorpus_LoadsGroups` covers all required corpus groups.\u0026#xA;2. `TestDocProseCorpus_ExpectedFindingSchema` validates golden normalized finding JSON.\u0026#xA;3. `TestDocProseCorpus_NegativeStructureCasesStayQuiet` covers paths, commands, IDs, tables, code spans, and frontmatter.\u0026#xA;4. `TestDocProseCorpus_PositiveCasesCanAssertRuleIDs` proves positives can require a specific DDx rule id.\u0026#xA;5. cd cli \u0026amp;\u0026amp; go test ./internal/docprose/... green.\u0026#xA;6. lefthook run pre-commit passes.\n    \u003c/acceptance\u003e\n    \u003clabels\u003ephase:2, are